Lab Name: File Path Traversal, Validation of File Extension with Null Byte Bypass

Category: Path Traversal

Difficulty: Practitioner

Objective: Retrieve the contents of the /etc/passwd file by bypassing file extension validation using a URL-encoded null byte.

Vulnerability Description

The application validates that the requested filename ends with the .png extension before accessing the file. However, it fails to handle URL-encoded null bytes correctly. By injecting a null byte (%00) before the required extension, the underlying filesystem treats the null byte as the end of the filename, causing the appended .png to be ignored.

Exploitation Steps

1. Open a product page and intercept the image request using Burp Suite.


2. Send the request to Repeater.


3. Locate the filename parameter.


4. Replace its value with the following payload:



../../../etc/passwd%00.png

5. Send the request.


6. The application validates the .png extension, but the null byte truncates the filename during file access, allowing the server to return the contents of /etc/passwd and solve the lab.

Payload

GET /image?filename=../../../etc/passwd%00.png HTTP/1.1

Why the Attack Works

The application only checks whether the supplied filename ends with .png. When %00 is decoded into a null byte, the underlying filesystem interprets it as the end of the string. Consequently, the effective filename becomes ../../../etc/passwd, while the .png extension is ignored, bypassing the validation.


Mitigation

Use modern APIs that safely handle string termination.

Canonicalize and validate file paths before access.

Reject null byte (%00) characters in user input.

Restrict file access to an allowlisted directory.

Do not rely solely on file extension validation for security.